# TypeScript Coding Standards

## Code Style
- **Semicolons**: Always use semicolons (enforced by ESLint)
- **Quotes**: Use single quotes (enforced by ESLint and Prettier)
- **Indentation**: 2 spaces (enforced by ESLint and Prettier)
- **Line endings**: Unix style (LF)
- **Trailing commas**: ES5 style (enforced by Prettier)
- **Print width**: 80 characters max

## TypeScript Best Practices
- **Strict mode**: Always enabled in [tsconfig.json](mdc:tsconfig.json)
- **Module resolution**: Use ES modules with bundler resolution
- **Type annotations**: Prefer explicit types for function parameters and return values
- **Interfaces**: Use interfaces for object shapes and function parameters
- **Type imports**: Use `import type` for type-only imports (enforced by ESLint)
- **No any types**: Avoid `any` type, use `unknown` or specific types instead
- **Readonly properties**: Use `readonly` for immutable data structures

## Node.js CLI Application Standards
- **Function naming**: Use camelCase for functions and variables
- **Class naming**: Use PascalCase for classes and interfaces
- **Error handling**: Use proper error types and meaningful error messages
- **Async/await**: Prefer async/await over Promise chains
- **Type safety**: Always provide explicit return types for public functions
- **Dependency injection**: Use constructor injection for better testability

## File Organization
- **Source files**: Place all source code in [src/](mdc:src/) directory
- **Entry points**: Use [src/index.ts](mdc:src/index.ts) for CLI applications
- **Module files**: One module per file with matching filename
- **Test files**: Mirror source structure in [tests/](mdc:tests/) directory
- **Examples**: Place example code in [src/examples/](mdc:src/examples/) directory

## Code Quality Rules (ESLint Enforced)
- **Function complexity**: Maximum complexity of 10 (enforced by ESLint)
- **Function length**: Maximum 100 lines per function (enforced by ESLint)
- **Parameter count**: Maximum 3 parameters per function (enforced by ESLint)
- **Nesting depth**: Maximum 4 levels of nesting (enforced by ESLint)
- **File length**: Maximum 300 lines per file (enforced by ESLint)
- **Unused variables**: Remove unused variables (enforced by ESLint)
- **Console usage**: Warn on console.log usage (enforced by ESLint)